on and medium\ngrades dull, weak: best weighty steers,\nearly 9.25: l.bOO lbs.. 9.15: most sales.\n7.25-8.50: big killers bearish on steers,\nalso on she stock: cutter-grade cows about\nsteady, beef cows weak; plainer quality\nconsidered heifers steady: mostly 8.00\ndown, best light offerings. 8.50: bulls\nfully steady at 0.75 down on sausage offer\ning:: vealers 25-50 lower; mostly ln.50\ndown: few. early. 11.00.\nSheep. 8.000: none direct: late Monday\nfat lambs. 15-25 higher than Friday; bulk\n8.00-75; 90-100 lbs.. 8.50-60; top \u2019ewes.\n4.75; today's trade steady; wooled lambs.\n95 lbs down. 8.50-75: choice clipped lambs,\n7.85; aro\u00abnd steady on sheep.\nCHICAGO PRODUCE.\nCHICAGO, March 1 OP:.\u2014Poultry, live,\n32 trucks. Hens firmer; balance steady.\nHens, over 5 lbs.. 20; 5 lbs. and less, 24;\nLeghorn hens. 19%; other prices un\nchanged.\nButter, 614.336: steady: prices un\nchanged. Eggs. 13,935: firmer. Fresh\nfaded extra firsts, local. 16%: cars, 17:\nfirsts, local. 10%; cars. 16%: current re\nceipts, 16; storage packed, extrrfs. 10%;\nfirsts. 19%.\nPotatoes. 115; on track. 364: total\nUnited States shipments. 657: old stock\ndull, slightly weaker undertone; supplies\nrather heavy: demand very slow: sacked\nper hundredweight. Idaho Russet Bur\nbanks. U. 8. No. 1. 1.32'/a-36: Colorado\nRed McClures. U. 8. No. 1. 1.40%-42%:\nNorth Dakota Bliss Triumphs. U. 8. No.\n1. 1.12%-15: Cobblers, U. S. No. 1. 1.07%;\nEarly Ohios, 90 per cent U. 8. No. 1, 1.15;\nWisconsin round whites. U. 8. No. 1. 1.00:\nMichigan Ausset Purals, U. 8. No. 1. 1.05;\nnew stock dull, supplies liberal, demand\nvery alow; track sales less than carlots.\nbushel crates. Florida Bliss Triumphs, U.\n8. No. 1, 1.30\nNEW YORK LIVE STOCK.\nNEW YORK. March 1 UP) (State Depart\nment of Agriculture).\u2014Cattle. 460. In\ncluding 370 direct. Total also Included four\nloads of show cattle and rejects from\nKnoxville. Tenn.. which unsold. Steers\nand bulls, nominal. Cows, steady: low\ncutter to cutter, 4.00-5.50; few fat cows\nto 6.25.\nVealers and calves. 1.760, Including\n1.740 direct. Vealers steady: few choice\nnearbys, 13.50; medium to good. 11.50\n12.00. Calves, nominal.\n8heep and lambs. 10.500 including 9.300\ndirect. Lambs slow; nothing done early:\nbids lower. Sheep, nominal.\nHogs. 3-250. Including 3,210 direct.\nMarket 15 higher; 197 sounds. 9.55.\nI\nAMERICAN SUGAR\nEARNS $4,143,138\n1937 Net Compares With\n$4,352,563 Recorded in\nPreceding Year.\nBy the Associated Freas.\nNEW YORK, March 1.\u2014American\nSugar Refining Co. today reported net\nIncome for 1937 was 94,143,138. This\ncompares with the 1936 net Income of\n94,332,563.\nAfter dividends of $7 per share on\nthe preferred, 1937 net income equals\n$2.20 earnings per common share,\ncompared with $2.67 for 1936, and an\nannual average of $6.51 for the 47\nyears of the company\u2019s operation.\nDividends totaling $2 per common\nshare were paid during 1937.\nThe company's annual report, signed\nby President Joseph F. Abbott, pointed\nparticularly to the fact that no strikes\ninterfered with negotiations with em\nployes\u2019 collective bargaining repre\nsentatives.\nWhile the company views with some\nconcern international competition, the\nreport says that with the temporary\nextension by Congress of limitations\non tropical refined sugar, domestic\nrefiners do not immediately face the\nneed to curtail employment in re\nfineries.\nBeerh-Nut Packing.\nBeech-Nut Packing Co., Nation-wide\ndistributors of packaged foods, reported\ntoday preliminary net profit in 1937\nwas $2,741,203, equal to $6.26 a share\non the common stock. This compared\nwith $2,709,309, or $6.19 in 1936.\nVick Chemical Co.\nVick Chemical Co. reported for six\nmonths ended December 31 indicated\nnet profit of 91.868.901, equal to $2.73\na share on the capital stock, compared\nwith $1,934,794, or $2.76 a share in\nthe comparable period a year earlier.\nThe company\u2019s laboratories are at\nGreensboro, N. C., and Philadelphia.\nLoose-Wiles Biscuit.\nLoose-Wiles Biscuit Co. reported\n1937 consolidated net income of $733,\n593, equal to $1.01 a share on the com\nmon stock, compared with $1,337,079,\nor $2.16 in 1936. The company\u2019s plants\nare in large cities throughout the\ncountry.\nDiamond Match Co.\nDiamond Match Co. reported for\n1937 net income of $2,111,959, equal\nto $1.73 a common share, against $2,\n056,031. or $1.65 in 1936. The com\npany's manufacturing and distribut\ning facilities are Nation-wide.\nEdward G. Budd Mfg.\nThe Edward G. Budd Manufactuing\nCo., maker of automobile bodies and\nother motor accessories and rail equip\nment, reported for 1937 net profit of\n$1,219,423, equal to 48 cents a share\non the common stock, compared w-ith\n$991,271, or 34 cents a share, in 1936.\nThe company has plants in Phila\ndelphia and Detroit.\nBudd Wheel Co.\nThe Budd Wheel Co., Detroit, manu\nfacturer of motor accessories, showed\n1937 profit of $618,991, equal to 60\ncents a share on the common stock,\nagainst $796,338, or 77 cents a share,\nin 1936.\nMarlin-Rockwell.\nThe Marlin-Rockwell Corp., maker\nof ball bearings, reported for 1937 net\nprofit of $1,900,620. equal to $5.60 a\nshare, against $1,634,111. or $4.81 a\nshare, in 1936. The company\u2019s plants\nare at Plainvilie, Conn.; Jamestown,\nN. IT., and Chicago.\nPlymouth Oil Co.\nPlymouth Oil Co. reported net in\ncome for year ended December 31,\n1937, of $2,935,342, equivalent to $2.85\na capital share. The total compares\nwith the previous year\u2019s $1,739,681, or\n$1.65 a share. Company was not liable\ntoi Federal surtax because of 1937\ndividend disbursements. January net\nincome was $236,091, or 23 cents a\nshare, compared with the January,\n1937. figure of $184,584, equivalent to\n18 cents a share.\n'Simmons Co.\nSimmons Co. and subsidiaries re\nported 1937 net profit of $3,314,251,\nequal to $2.88 a share of capital stock,\ncompared with $4,003,306, or $3.53 a\nshare, in 1936. The company, manu\nfacturer of mattresses and beds, has\nplants throughout the country.\nJ. J. Newberry Co.\nJ. J. Newberry Co. and subsidiaries,\noperators of a national chain of variety\nstores, reported 1937 net income of\n$2,255,454 after charges and pro\nvision for Federal surtax, equal to\n$5.27 a share of common stock, against\n$2,570,286, or $6.03 a share, in 1936.\nServel, Inc.\nServel, Inc., refrigerator manufac\nturers, with a plant at Evansville, Ind.,\nreported net income for quarter ended\nJanuary 31, 1938, of $33,183. equal,\nafter preferred requirements, to 1 cent\na share. This compares with the year\nago figure of $388,186, or 21 cents per\nshare.\nScovill Manufacturing Co.\nScovill Manufacturing Co., metal\nworking and machinery concern, re\nported net income of $1,457,783 for\n1937 after customary charges but be\nfore $207,922 special inventory re\nserve. In 1936 net profit was $3,151,\n180 before $500,299 inventory reserve.\n\"Hants are maintained at Waterbury,\nConn.; Brooklyn, Akron and Tbronto.\nSHORT-TERM SECURITIES.\n(Reported by Smith. Barney Co.)\nBid. Asked.\nAmer Tel A Tel 574s '43 113'/, 113*4\nAuburn Auto Co 4*48 '30 __ 21*, 3H\nAustin Northw 5s \u20194I__ 83 88\nBaldw Loco Wks 5s '40 __ 101 *i\nCalil Pck Corp Es 40_ 104 104*,\nCentral Foundry fis '41 __ 115\nChesap Ohio Ry 5s \u201939.- 10444 105\nContainer Corp 5s '43 87'/, 80\nCuba Northern Rys 5 74s \u201942 3874 387,\nDelaware Hud 4s '43 _. 5074 5144\nEdison El Ilium 4s '39_ 10174 1007,\nOen Pub Serv 574s \u201939 9974\nOrand Rap Ind 474s '4110074\nHouston Oil 5'4s '40 __ 10044 101*4\nIllinois Steel 474s '40 __ 105 10574\nInter Mer Marine 6s '41 __ 4674 50\nInter Tel A Tel 474s '30._ 8744 8874\nLaclede Gas Light 6s '30._ 87 88\nLake Erie A West 5s '41_ __ 89\nLehigh Val Ter Ry 5s '41 7074\nLoulsv Nash R R 4s \u201940 103 10374\nMich Cen R R 4s \"40 _ 100\nMidland R R of N J 5s '40. 1674 19V,\nMilw Nor R R 4\u20184s '39 51 7474\nNew York Tel Co 4H! \u201939 _ 106 10644\nPennsylvania Co 374s \u201941 _ 103 10