\nThree weeks ago it was understood\nthat the banking interests heavily\nbacking Transcontinental Western\nAir., Inc., were attempting to acquire\nEastern Air.\nInquiry in responsible quarters yes\nterday elicited only the Information\nthat if General Motors was negotiating\nfor sale of Its stock in N. A. A., or If\nsale of the airline was contemplated,\n\u201cnot enough progress has been made\nto deserve mention.\u201d\nWorkers Televised.\nVisits to industrial establishments\nare being televised by London\u2019s mobile\ntelevision unit. Recent afternoon and\nevening broadcasts were made from a\nphonograph plant. The recordings of\nan orchestra of 30 pieces, of a chorus\nof 12 and of several soloists were tele\nvised.\nOutlook Still Too Uncertain\nto Warrant Declaration,\nPresident Says.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNBW YORK March 1.\u2014Directors of\nJohns-Manvllle Corp., manufacturer*\nof asbestos, roofings and other building\nmaterials, yesterday omitted the divi\ndend on common stock due at this\ntime.\nLast quarter the company paid an\nextra common dividend of $1 a share,\nalong with the regular dividend of 75\ncents a common share, compared with\n$4.25 a share in 1936.\n\u201cThe business outlook for the imme\ndiate future is still too uncertain to\nwarrant the declaration of dividends\non the common stock, based on antici\npation of profits,\u201d said Lewis H. Brown,\npresident, commenting on the omis\nsion.\nThe board, however, voted the regu\nlar dividend of $1.75 a share on the\ncumulative 7 per cent preferred stock,\npayable April 1 to holders of record\nMarch 17.\nAmerican Smelting.\nAmerican Smelting Refining Co.\ntoday declared a dividend of 50 cent*\non the common stock, payable May 31\nto stock of record May 6. Last divi\ndend, 75 cents, was paid yesterday.\nPayments in 1937 were 75 cents each\nFebruary, 27, May 29, August 31; $1.75\nNovember 30 and $1, special, De\ncember 22.\nstatement or the condition\nOf the\nREPUBLIC\nINSURANCE CO.\nDALLAS, TEXA